<HEAD>Jamaican Court Orders Sale of Marley Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Appeals Court ordered on Tuesday
that reggae singer Bob Marley's estate be sold for $8.6 million to
the New York-based recording company Island Logic.
   Marley's widow, reggae singer Rita Marley, and lawyers for his 11
children had argued that the price was too low and appealed earlier
approval of the sale by the estate's administrator, a Kingston bank.
   Marley, 36, died of cancer in May 1981 in a Miami hospital
without leaving a will.
   Judge Ira Rowe upheld the sale and ordered that Island Logic pay
for the estate at once and not over a 10-year period as proposed
originally.
   Assets include Marley's song catalogs valued at $5.3 million, $3
million in recording royalties and record distribution rights,
recording equipment, and real estate in Jamaica.
   Marley was survived by his mother, his wife and their four
children, and seven other children born to seven different women.
   On Feb. 22, his four children by his wife, who perform as Ziggy
Marley and the Melody Makers, won the reggae music section of the
Grammy awards in Los Angeles with their album ``Conscious Party.''
</TEXT>
