<LEADPARA>  The Jamaican Supreme Court last week ended a bitter 10-year-old struggle over
reggae superstar Bob Marley's estate by approving a deal granting rights to
Island Records founder Chris Blackwell and Rita Marley, the singer's widow.
The Blackwell-Marley bid of $11.5 million prevailed over MCA-Matsushita's
higher offer of $15.2 million.;   The winning bid, placed by Rita Marley and
her four children, backed by Blackwell and his Island Logic company, ends a
decade of often emotional and bitter struggle over Marley's estate, which
includes his publishing copyrights, recording royalties, a recording studio
and some real estate. The singer died intestate.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MARLEY'S WIDOW WINS RIGHTS TO ESTATE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Rita Marley fought hard to keep what she said was her legacy and argued her
case on emotional grounds in both the Jamaican courts and the world press.
Blackwell, a Jamaican by birth, has been associated with Marley since the
singer's early days. (box)  </TEXT>
