<LEADPARA>  Ten years after Bob Marley's death, reggae is still here. And in some ways,
it's thriving. UB40's "Here I Am Come And Take Me" is a top single. Ziggy
Marley's album "Jahmekya" is everywhere. And Maxi Priest, Steel Pulse,
Shinehead, Burning Spear and other top reggae groups are all on tour.;    The
beat goes on. But what about the politics?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REGGAE REVOLUTION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Trends
What's Hot  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Marley, above, called for Third World liberation, and kept the fight up
right to his death. The liberation that reggae star Shabba Ranks is interested
most in is sexual. And other reggae stars are avoiding politics to focus on
stylish soul.;    But Marley's family is still carrying on his message. And
his music is still helping people everywhere to carry on.;  GETTING OUT; (box)
TONIGHT: Modern Art rocks picturesquely at McNeils, 800 Kiely Blvd, Santa
Clara. (408) 244-4195.  </TEXT>
