<HEAD>The Best and Worst in Film, Music and Theater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the year of a colossal flop and a colossal triumph on
Broadway, of strikes and turmoil in Hollywood, of a pop-music
bullseye in Dublin.
   Here are the best and worst in film, theater and pop music in
1988, as compiled by Bob Thomas, film critic and Hollywood reporter
for The Associated Press; Michael Kuchwara, AP drama writer, and the
AP's music critics:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MOVIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Best:
   _ `'' Drunks aren't funny anymore.
   _ ``Full Moon in Blue Water.'' A regional-theater
play-in-progress.
   _ ``The Lair of the White Worm.'' The pits from Ken Russell.
   _ ``The Seventh Sign.'' ``The Exorcist'' without brains.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THEATER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Best:
   _ ``The Phantom of the Opera.'' The year's biggest hit and its
best musical. Andrew Lloyd Webber produced his most accomplished
score to date _ lush, romantic and sweeping music that perfectly
captured Gaston Leroux's passionate tale of love denied.
   _ ``M. Butterfly.'' David Henry Hwang's brilliant recreation of a
spy scandal and love affair involving a French diplomat and a
Chinese opera singer who turns out to be a man.
   _ ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone.'' August Wilson's story of the
search for identity among the children of slaves.
   _ ``The Road to Mecca.'' Athol Fugard's tale of one woman's
determination to remain independent.
   _ ``Speed-the-Plow.'' David Mamet's scathing look at Hollywood
greed and glory.
   _ ``The Cocktail Hour.'' A.R. Gurney's comic examination of
upper-class generational conflict.
   
   Worst:
   _ ``Carrie.'' An $8 million disaster, Broadway's most expensive
flop. It was based on the Stephen King horror novel about a dumpy,
awkward teen-age girl with telekinetic powers. Betty Buckley and
16-year-old Linzi Hateley, in the title role, sang their hearts out,
but nothing could save this dud.
   _ ``Chess.'' Another turkey that signaled that the British
musical domination of Broadway was over. Despite its good score by
Tim Rice and members of ABBA, it died because of a deadly book by
Richard Nelson and turgid direction by Trevor Nunn.
   _ ``Julius Caesar.'' Al Pacino and Martin Sheen brought Hollywood
glitz but nothing else to ``Julius Caesar.'' The two stars, along
with Edward Herrmann, massacred Shakespeare.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>POP MUSIC</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Best:
   _ ``Rattle and Hum,'' U2. An ambitious, important and satisfying
record. The Irish superstars swing wildly at numerous musical
styles, and more often than not hit the mark in their part-live,
part-studio double album.
   _ ``Tracy Chapman,'' Tracy Chapman. Stirring songs of love and
social conscience from the year's most distinctive new voice. Sets
one to wondering if Chapman is An Important Artist For The 1990s or
a folkie with a few great songs who just got a break. Her big tour
didn't answer the question; her next album will.
   _ ``The Mona Lisa's Sister,'' Graham Parker. A fine comeback by a
brilliant artist all but given up for dead. Parker, one of the '70s
finest songwriters, is caustic, as ever, but this literate and
listenable record shows more facets of the man than anything he's
done in years.
   _ ``Talk Is Cheap,'' Keith Richards. No, Keith Richards can't
sing. But this is rousing, rocking, flat-out fun _ a raunchy,
whiskey-soaked collection of songs with not a single frill attached.
The only problem with ``Talk Is Cheap'' is that its release has
revived childish arguments over who's the coolest, Mick or Keith.
Well, we've always known it's Keith, haven't we?
   _ ``Conscious Party,'' Ziggy Marley. The son of reggae legend Bob
Marley delivers a sparkling debut. Ziggy appears to have his late
father's knack for sharp, topical songs that also are danceable.
   
   Worst:
   _ ``Baby I Love Your Way-Free Bird Medley,'' Will To Power. All
the worst memories of the '70s come rushing back, sort of like a bad
meal.
   _ ``Don't You Know What the Night Can Do,'' Steve Winwood. Is it
a song? Is it a commercial? Only his accountant knows for sure.
   _ ``Heavy Nova,'' Robert Palmer. He sold his soul for a hit, and
this is our payback.
   _ ``Brian Wilson.'' Far from the triumphant comeback some
proclaimed. Wishing doesn't make it so.
   _ ``Hysteria,'' Def Leppard. Nothing could be worse.
</TEXT>
