<HEAD>Late Reggae Star's Brother Killed In Police Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shotgun-waving young man who was killed by police
after he stalked through a shopping mall was identified Monday as a
brother of late reggae music star Bob Marley.
   Police said they hadn't been able to explain the actions of
Anthony Booker, 19.
   ``The investigation's still going on. We don't have many
details,'' said Metro-Dade Police Lt. Glen Kay.
   Police were called to busy Cutler Ridge Mall around 3:30 p.m.
Sunday after customers saw a tall, thin young man dressed in white
and carrying a pistol-gripped .12-gauge shotgun. The man was
railing incoherently and mumbling to himself, witnesses told police.
   ``He was really mad. He was looking for someone,'' said shopper
Carol Williams, who said she was shopping with her two small
children when Booker pointed the shotgun at her, then continued on
his way.
   ``He was saying: `I'm gonna get you. I'm gonna get you,''' she
said.
   Shoppers scattered as the gunman walked through the mall until
police arrived.
   As an off-duty Miami police officer chased him, a police
helicopter hovered overhead and Metro-Dade police moved in, the
gunman ran through the mall parking lot, police said.
   He fired at least once. Officers returned fire, killing him,
police said.
   Booker's mother, Cedella Booker, said she didn't know what
caused her son to go to the mall with a gun.
   ``He is just a ... humble young man. When I saw him yesterday,
he didn't look like my son,'' she said.
   Friends and relatives said he had seemed upset since returning
last week from a trip to his homeland of Jamaica. They said he
hadn't been in trouble before and aspired to be a musician.
   Bob Marley, who brought the reggae music of Jamaica to
international prominence, died in Miami of a brain tumor in 1981.
</TEXT>
