<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A towel used to mop the brow of George
Harrison during his 1975 ``Dark Horse'' concert tour will be
auctioned to raise funds for abused children.
   The towel, signed by the former Beatle, is to be sold Wednesday
at an auction to benefit Try Angle House in Nashville for abused and
neglected girls, auction spokeswoman Patsi Cox said Friday.
   The towel was donated by an unidentified local musician who has
worked with Harrison. About 100 items once owned or used by
celebrities will be auctioned.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cyclist Greg LeMond will display his speed
in the saddle in a $12-million advertising campaign for fast-food
tacos.
   A commercial scheduled to begin airing Monday features LeMond
making a ``Run to the Border'' for six-pack boxes of Taco Bell
tacos, said Tim Ryan, the restaurant chain's senior vice president
of marketing.
   LeMond signed last year with Taco Bell Corp. after winning the
Tour de France, cycling's premier event.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBION, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Katie Kelly, who quit her job as a movie
critic on ``Entertainment Tonight'' to teach English to children in
Vietnam, is a hit in her hometown.
   Today was Katie Kelly Day in Albion, a town of 2,000 about 140
miles northwest of Omaha.
   Ms. Kelly has been tutoring Amerasians in Vietnam since March.
She described her work as ``an experience of a lifetime; I wouldn't
have passed it up.''
   Vietnam, she said, ``has grabbed me by the heart. The people are
absolutely incredible _ friendly, social, generous. They have
nothing, but they'd give you the shirt off their back.''
   Ms. Kelly's works in the Amerasian Transient Center, recently
constructed by the U.S. government in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly
Saigon. Her students have ranged in age from 5 to 51.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handful of Baptist ministers complained
that Pat Conroy's use of profanity in some of his best-selling
novels made him unsuitable as Furman University's commencement
speaker.
   Conroy, whose books include ``The Lords of Discipline,'' ``The
Prince of Tides'' and ``The Great Santini,'' was to give Furman's
commencement address today.
   The clergymen sent protest letters to John E. Johns, president of
the private college of 2,500 students founded by Baptists and
supported by the South Carolina Baptist Convention.
   ``I have nothing against Pat Conroy, but with Furman supposedly
being a Christian and a Southern Baptist school, I don't think he
should be receiving an honorary degree,'' said David Satterwhite, a
minister at Roebuck Baptist Church in Spartanburg.
   Johns said the college was honoring Conroy ``as an outstanding
novelist and script writer'' and would not withdraw the invitation.
   Conroy on Friday welcomed the ministers to his speech.
   ``It will probably be a far more interesting speech than the
sermons they give on Sunday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge allowed actor Todd Bridges to remain
free on $25,000 bail pending his trial on an assault charge but
warned he would be sent to jail if he shows up in court under the
influence of drugs.
   ``There were two appearances when I suspected you were under the
influence of narcotics,'' Superior Court Judge Florence Cooper said
Friday. ``But on this and another occasion, you gave the impression
your conduct has improved.''
   On April 9, Bridges told the judge he failed to make a previous
appearance because he was involved in a car accident on his way to
the courthouse.
   Bridges, the former child star of television's ``Diff'rent
Strokes,'' is to go on trial July 30 on a felony assault charge
stemming from the Feb. 2 shooting of an unarmed man in a Los Angeles
house where drugs were on sale.
   Bridges was acquitted of attempted murder and involuntary
manslaughter in the shooting of Kenneth ``Tex'' Clay. Bridges
testified he was too high on cocaine to remember what happened.
   Jurors could not reach a verdict on the charge of assault with a
deadly weapon, and prosecutors refiled that charge.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Marley's widow, Alfarita, has been sued
for $10 million for allegedly reneging on promises to perform in
Hawaii.
   Anthony Spence, owner of Premiere Productions, filed the lawsuit
Friday in U.S. District Court alleging that the late reggae star's
widow agreed to perform three concerts in Hawaii in the summer of
1988 and also promised Premiere future concert dates with her son,
Ziggy.
   According to the lawsuit, Premiere advanced Mrs. Marley $22,500
and sent her 15 airplane tickets worth $15,126. The day she was
scheduled to arrive in Hawaii, she canceled, saying bronchitis
prevented her from making the trip, the lawsuit says.
   Spence says she returned only $10,000 of the advance and five
tickets.
   A woman who answered the telephone at the number listed for
Marley's home in Kingston, Jamaica, said the performer was out of
the country and could not be reached for comment.
   Spence is asking for all of the money to be returned plus $10
million in damages for breach of contract and fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

